And that was that.

01:36:02.020 --> 01:36:03.500
Or samples of.

01:36:04.020 --> 01:36:07.220
Of whatever it was it was picking up and finding.

01:36:07.760 --> 01:36:09.360
Because it was out searching.

01:36:09.760 --> 01:36:12.120
It's like this automated drone sort of thing.

01:36:12.120 --> 01:36:13.160
Automated drone, yeah.

01:36:14.380 --> 01:36:20.260
And I believe Colonel John Alexander knew about Rendlesham before just about anybody else in the United States.

01:36:20.260 --> 01:36:21.120
Probably so, yeah.

01:36:21.120 --> 01:36:24.460
Was he involved in your, I guess you can't probably say or.

01:36:24.820 --> 01:36:32.740
No, John was rarely, I don't think he was ever involved in our unit.

01:36:32.820 --> 01:36:33.120
Okay.

01:36:33.120 --> 01:36:41.260
But Bert, Albert Stubblebine, General Stubblebine, became a really good friend.

01:36:41.260 --> 01:36:42.320
And I always called him Bert.

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:48.960
And Bert intentionally kept him out of it.

01:36:49.460 --> 01:36:56.600
Albert Stubblebine is a very interesting figure who seems very conspiratorial himself.

01:36:56.600 --> 01:36:58.980
He became like a second father to me.

01:36:59.160 --> 01:37:00.760
I just treasure that man.

01:37:01.640 --> 01:37:04.440
What is his, tell us about him.

01:37:04.480 --> 01:37:07.600
Because he's this very intriguing figure in kind of UFO lore.

01:37:07.600 --> 01:37:13.340
Like when Stephen Greer, for example, initially gets into all this stuff.

01:37:13.380 --> 01:37:15.840
He sort of, he was this emergency medical doctor.

01:37:15.840 --> 01:37:19.840
And then he developed CE5, this protocol to sort of call in UFOs.

01:37:20.160 --> 01:37:28.200
And Stubblebine is first on the scene to, you know, ostensibly try to almost recruit him into some sort of government program.

01:37:28.860 --> 01:37:28.920
Yeah.

01:37:29.340 --> 01:37:31.640
So what is, what is Stubblebine like?

01:37:31.640 --> 01:37:32.740
Bert was very interested in it.

01:37:32.740 --> 01:37:41.360
Bert had the project going where he had people out looking for PK events and things like this.

01:37:41.480 --> 01:37:49.200
That's how, that's how I got reported to Bert, who was head of the Intelligence and Security Command.

01:37:49.560 --> 01:37:54.140
That's why he came out to the unit and wanted to talk to me.

01:37:54.880 --> 01:37:59.920
And at that, we've seen the movie, The Man Who Stare at Goats.

01:38:00.120 --> 01:38:00.360
Yeah.

01:38:00.360 --> 01:38:08.760
He shoved me into the office and told the commander, I need to talk to Sergeant Buchanan and get out, you know.

01:38:09.060 --> 01:38:16.000
He turned to me and got up in my face and said, did you kill my computers with your mind?

01:38:17.160 --> 01:38:20.360
And I thought, I have got to lie about this.

01:38:21.460 --> 01:38:22.660
I knew I had.

01:38:22.660 --> 01:38:26.860
And I could see my grandchildren paying for computers.

01:38:27.560 --> 01:38:31.120
You know, basically, I heard myself say, yes, sir, I did.

01:38:31.120 --> 01:38:44.580
And the grin that comes across General Hapgood's face in that movie is exactly the grin that came across Bert's face.

01:38:45.320 --> 01:38:49.360
And you can, you can blip this out if you want.

01:38:50.660 --> 01:38:57.700
Just immediately right there in my face, he said, far fucking out have I ever got a job for you.

01:38:57.700 --> 01:38:59.600
Ah, that's awesome.

01:38:59.840 --> 01:39:00.080
Yeah.

01:39:00.640 --> 01:39:01.080
Wow.

01:39:01.380 --> 01:39:01.560
Yeah.

01:39:02.080 --> 01:39:08.080
Who do you think tasked him initially with assembling this X-Men team of Psychic?

01:39:08.080 --> 01:39:09.620
I think he did it all on his own.

01:39:09.740 --> 01:39:11.480
He got all kinds of flack from that.

01:39:11.840 --> 01:39:12.160
Really?

01:39:12.260 --> 01:39:13.140
He really did.

01:39:13.240 --> 01:39:14.860
So he kind of went rogue a little bit.

01:39:15.020 --> 01:39:15.240
Yeah.

01:39:15.740 --> 01:39:16.040
Hmm.

01:39:16.040 --> 01:39:20.560
Such a fascinating world, you know, all of this stuff.

01:39:20.660 --> 01:39:28.300
And I always, I find it interesting too, because you have Hal Puthoff is one of these guys who's kind of, you know, one of the godfathers of remote viewing.

01:39:28.460 --> 01:39:28.940
He's great.

01:39:29.180 --> 01:39:30.020
Amazing guy.

01:39:30.140 --> 01:39:30.360
Yeah.

01:39:30.680 --> 01:39:34.160
And, but then he also is at the forefront of the UFO stuff.

01:39:34.280 --> 01:39:35.760
And that has to be significant.

01:39:35.760 --> 01:39:37.340
Like, to me, at least.

01:39:37.340 --> 01:39:42.360
I think there has to be this, like, essential overlap between these two things.

01:39:43.980 --> 01:39:44.460
Okay.

01:39:44.840 --> 01:39:44.900
Yeah.

01:39:46.040 --> 01:39:55.860
Um, you've heard a lot of stories that when a person gets abducted, they suddenly start having psychic ability?

01:39:56.460 --> 01:39:56.800
Yes.

01:39:57.200 --> 01:39:57.540
Okay.

01:39:58.200 --> 01:40:04.480
I was tasked to do a paper that, as soon as I turned it in, it disappeared.

01:40:04.480 --> 01:40:15.660
I don't know if it's in that place where, that big warehouse where, at the end of the Indiana Jones movie.

01:40:16.040 --> 01:40:26.480
The task was compare and contrast our psychic ability with the E.T. psychic ability.

01:40:26.480 --> 01:40:35.360
And, um, I got access to a bunch of stuff that most people will never see.

01:40:35.420 --> 01:40:48.000
But, um, the end result of that study that I did, I had already found out that you can divide psychically the E.T.s into four different groups.

01:40:48.000 --> 01:40:57.940
Uh, there's not us and them, there's us and them and them and them and them and them and them and them and them and them and them and you can cut them into four different groups, friends and enemies.

01:40:57.940 --> 01:41:06.600
Um, and those who have more psychic ability than we have and those who are equal or less psychic than we are.

01:41:06.600 --> 01:41:14.260
Um, the enemies who are equal or less than we are try to stay away from here.

01:41:14.260 --> 01:41:16.320
They don't like us, they don't like us, okay?

01:41:17.320 --> 01:41:25.120
The friends who are less or equal to us psychically come here for trade.

01:41:26.180 --> 01:41:27.520
Come here for trade.

01:41:28.400 --> 01:41:37.040
And, um, the ones who are more psychic than we are and friends want us to become psychic.

01:41:37.040 --> 01:41:45.940
The ones who are enemies and more psychic than we are don't want us off this planet.

01:41:46.340 --> 01:41:51.480
They'd be very happy to just wipe the planet off, you know, kill all humans, period.

01:41:52.220 --> 01:41:54.440
And, uh, I couldn't figure out why.

01:41:55.260 --> 01:42:05.340
And this one, um, this one event that I got the record of, there were three guys camping at a lake.

01:42:05.340 --> 01:42:13.940
And they, it was nighttime, they saw a UFO come, and they were standing there on the lake looking at it.

01:42:14.420 --> 01:42:21.060
It came up right over them, and all of a sudden they couldn't move, they were frozen, and they got abducted.

01:42:22.500 --> 01:42:33.720
And there was something about that that, uh, sort of just made everything that I had studied before that fall together.

01:42:33.720 --> 01:42:42.780
And that is that those ETs had much more psychic ability than the humans, but no range.

01:42:43.960 --> 01:42:47.480
They had to be right over them in order to do anything.

01:42:48.200 --> 01:42:57.360
With the remote viewing, we can see across space and time, like looking across the room at a stove or something, you know?

01:42:57.360 --> 01:42:57.960
Mm-hmm.

01:42:57.960 --> 01:42:58.660
No different.

01:42:59.660 --> 01:43:09.760
If we develop our psychic ability, when we get out into space, we are going to be a power in the universe,

01:43:09.820 --> 01:43:16.820
because we can see way into the future, anywhere in space, and all that.

01:43:17.380 --> 01:43:19.380
And evidently they can't.

01:43:19.640 --> 01:43:20.000
Mm-hmm.

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:22.740
And so we have that ability.

01:43:23.280 --> 01:43:31.240
That's why our friends want us out there, and our enemies don't want us off this planet.

01:43:32.000 --> 01:43:38.960
Do you have a sense of, like, taxonomies of non-human intelligence, like the species and stuff?

01:43:38.960 --> 01:43:47.480
Because I'm not going to lie, when I speak to people about, when people volunteer information about this, I'm often skeptical.

01:43:47.840 --> 01:43:54.800
And then in the event in which we are, you know, being visited by non-human intelligence, which I believe we are.

01:43:54.920 --> 01:43:55.240
Oh, yeah.

01:43:55.420 --> 01:44:01.160
Then it's somehow obviously very important to categorize them, as you just have.

01:44:01.220 --> 01:44:06.180
But can you categorize them further by they're from XYZ planet, you know?

01:44:06.240 --> 01:44:07.840
Oh, you mean in those four groups?

01:44:07.840 --> 01:44:11.700
Yeah, I mean, like, the classic thing would be, like, Nordic greys, reptilians, like—

01:44:11.700 --> 01:44:18.620
What I found was that, like, the Nordics, the greys, and all that fit into all four groups.

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:19.400
Mm-hmm.

01:44:19.400 --> 01:44:30.680
So there are greys that hate us, greys that like us, greys that are more psychic than we are, greys that couldn't view their way out of a paper bag if the top was open, you know?

01:44:30.680 --> 01:44:31.300
Mm-hmm.

01:44:31.300 --> 01:44:33.660
And like many of us.

01:44:33.660 --> 01:45:01.340
And that there was no—seemed to be no separating them, according to type, into any of those four groups that—at some point, there are people in any of those four groups that—I mean, in any race that fit into all those four groups.

01:45:01.340 --> 01:45:04.960
Have you ever seen a UFO in a hangar?

01:45:05.760 --> 01:45:06.940
Not in a hangar.

01:45:07.500 --> 01:45:15.340
Well, in the viewing of Mount Hayes, Mount Zeal.

01:45:15.340 --> 01:45:20.660
Have you ever seen a UFO in the possession of the American military?

01:45:20.900 --> 01:45:25.420
Not just a UFO that's flying around, you know, in the woods somewhere or something or whatever?

01:45:25.420 --> 01:45:41.220
The only one I've seen was in that hangar where the collision had taken place, and there was just a massive dump of debris, and that control panel was there in that debris.

01:45:41.460 --> 01:45:42.880
And so where was this?

01:45:43.040 --> 01:45:43.920
Where did you see this?

01:45:43.920 --> 01:45:47.740
You're back to where I can't answer.

01:45:48.140 --> 01:45:48.620
Can't answer.

01:45:50.400 --> 01:45:53.980
But so you must have had a very high clearance at the time?

01:45:54.620 --> 01:45:54.940
Oh, yeah.

01:45:55.020 --> 01:46:05.900
I had one of the highest clearances, not only for the remote viewing, but for other stuff that I've done that will never be talked about.

01:46:05.900 --> 01:46:11.740
And I've heard that only 17 people have ever had that.

01:46:12.120 --> 01:46:12.460
Really?

01:46:12.520 --> 01:46:13.980
I don't know if that's true or not.

01:46:14.240 --> 01:46:17.060
So it's basically the highest clearance you can get?

01:46:17.060 --> 01:46:24.800
Oh, when I was given that clearance, he said, that's the highest clearance I've ever given anybody.

01:46:25.480 --> 01:46:27.680
And I said, well, what is the highest clearance?

01:46:28.680 --> 01:46:31.800
He said, oh, there is one, but nobody ever gets it.

01:46:32.160 --> 01:46:33.100
And I said, what's that?

01:46:33.100 --> 01:46:34.500
And he said, truth.

01:46:36.600 --> 01:46:37.000
Truth.

01:46:37.400 --> 01:46:38.160
I like that.

01:46:38.240 --> 01:46:38.560
Truth.

01:46:38.700 --> 01:46:40.020
Nobody learns the truth.

01:46:40.060 --> 01:46:40.780
Yeah, that's funny.

01:46:41.240 --> 01:46:45.500
But you had the highest human clearance in the federal government.

01:46:45.500 --> 01:46:49.420
I just, I had the highest clearance of anybody I've ever met.

01:46:49.740 --> 01:46:49.820
Okay.

01:46:49.920 --> 01:46:55.400
And one time, Bert and I were out at lunch, and he said, what is your clearance?

01:46:55.540 --> 01:47:00.440
And I said, T-S-E-S-I-S-I-O-P.

01:47:01.580 --> 01:47:07.900
And his utensils went down, and he said, what?

01:47:08.240 --> 01:47:10.320
He said, I can't even get that.

01:47:12.460 --> 01:47:12.900
Oh.

01:47:12.900 --> 01:47:21.640
And so, anyway, but it was because of other work that, outside of the remote viewing unit

01:47:21.640 --> 01:47:27.460
and outside of all the other that I was doing.

01:47:28.840 --> 01:47:32.640
Well, I think that clearance needs a little bit of a rebrand for our audience.

01:47:32.760 --> 01:47:35.500
That is not PSYOP psychological operation.

01:47:35.600 --> 01:47:36.120
No, it's not.

01:47:36.460 --> 01:47:40.540
It's Strategic Integrated Operation, S-I-O-P.

01:47:40.600 --> 01:47:41.800
S-I-O-P.

01:47:41.800 --> 01:47:42.240
Yeah.

01:47:42.240 --> 01:47:43.560
So, don't get any ideas.

01:47:43.860 --> 01:47:44.020
No.

01:47:44.020 --> 01:47:50.440
But this UFO that you saw the debris of in a hangar, did you see that in person?

01:47:50.900 --> 01:47:51.100
Yeah.

01:47:51.440 --> 01:47:52.960
So, that wasn't a remote viewing session.

01:47:53.660 --> 01:47:55.140
No, that wasn't a remote view.

01:47:55.140 --> 01:47:56.540
I was standing there in front of it.

01:47:56.880 --> 01:48:00.220
You were standing in front of a crashed UFO in a hangar.

01:48:00.220 --> 01:48:04.760
And this hangar was dealing with mid-air collisions.

01:48:04.760 --> 01:48:12.580
And so, the guy, my friend was showing me around and showing me how they put the planes back together and all that.

01:48:12.820 --> 01:48:19.760
And they had these piles of rubble all over and they were, you know, to figure out what happened with the mid-air collision.

01:48:19.760 --> 01:48:21.280
And we passed by this one.

01:48:21.280 --> 01:48:26.180
And here was the control panel of a UFO, which I had seen and operated before.

01:48:26.180 --> 01:48:31.560
And I said, that's out of UFO.

01:48:31.560 --> 01:48:38.960
And it echoed in this metal Quonset building.

01:48:38.960 --> 01:48:51.600
And immediately, the colonel who was in charge came running out of his office and, I mean, just ran me out of the place.

01:48:52.900 --> 01:48:55.620
A lot of questions.

01:48:56.100 --> 01:48:57.900
So, you said something interesting there.

01:48:57.960 --> 01:49:00.140
You said, which I had operated before.

01:49:00.140 --> 01:49:07.280
So, you knew that this was a UFO control panel because you had some prior experience with it?

01:49:07.280 --> 01:49:12.660
I had a—I was abducted, okay?

01:49:13.580 --> 01:49:19.060
I was a Methodist minister in East Texas.

01:49:19.060 --> 01:49:30.100
And the Methodists used—they moved their young preachers around from church to church to give them experience.

01:49:30.740 --> 01:49:32.780
Every year, you move to a different church.

01:49:33.400 --> 01:49:35.180
And it was time to move.

01:49:35.640 --> 01:49:38.640
My family had already moved to the new parsonage.

01:49:38.920 --> 01:49:40.320
And when you say parsonage—

01:49:40.320 --> 01:49:43.100
Parsonage is where the preacher lives.

01:49:43.260 --> 01:49:44.820
It's the house where the preacher lives.

01:49:44.880 --> 01:49:45.200
Okay.

01:49:45.200 --> 01:49:49.160
I was cleaning out the old parsonage, got it all cleaned out.

01:49:49.260 --> 01:49:50.540
Everything was in the U-Haul.

01:49:51.760 --> 01:49:54.180
And it was late at night.

01:49:55.000 --> 01:49:56.140
And I was tired.

01:49:56.340 --> 01:50:02.520
So, I made a pallet down on the living room floor and laid down.

01:50:03.360 --> 01:50:08.080
And I was wide awake.

01:50:09.440 --> 01:50:11.740
And I heard something laying in the backyard.

01:50:11.740 --> 01:50:15.940
Now, this was a country church.

01:50:16.640 --> 01:50:23.480
We were over a quarter mile off the nearest road in the woods and all that.

01:50:24.020 --> 01:50:28.000
And I heard something land in the backyard.

01:50:29.240 --> 01:50:31.560
And I knew it wasn't a helicopter.

01:50:32.700 --> 01:50:34.300
It didn't sound like a helicopter.

01:50:34.300 --> 01:50:50.980
It sounded like—the best example I can give is where some kid sticks a playing card into the spokes of his bicycle and, you know, it was like that.

01:50:51.880 --> 01:50:59.100
And so, I was going to get up and go to the back room and see what was in the backyard.

01:50:59.500 --> 01:51:00.740
I couldn't move.

01:51:00.980 --> 01:51:02.140
And I was wide awake.

01:51:02.240 --> 01:51:04.020
It wasn't sleep paralysis at all.

01:51:04.020 --> 01:51:05.000
I was wide awake.

01:51:05.440 --> 01:51:06.580
I couldn't move.

01:51:07.300 --> 01:51:13.420
And I heard somebody walking around the house to the front window looking in.

01:51:15.320 --> 01:51:17.820
And immediately, I woke up.

01:51:18.520 --> 01:51:21.320
And I was sitting in a white room.

01:51:22.360 --> 01:51:23.980
There were two rows of seats.

01:51:23.980 --> 01:51:27.700
And I was sitting here.

01:51:28.340 --> 01:51:32.280
There was an elderly, elderly woman sitting here.

01:51:32.760 --> 01:51:35.160
I tried talking to her, and she was just frozen.

01:51:35.940 --> 01:51:38.080
And there were empty seats over here in the window.

01:51:38.080 --> 01:51:43.880
Now, when I fly, I have to have a window seat.

01:51:44.520 --> 01:51:47.660
I can't deal with being inside.

01:51:48.020 --> 01:51:49.840
You know, I have to have a window seat.

01:51:49.900 --> 01:51:50.840
Especially on a UFO.

01:51:50.840 --> 01:51:53.260
Well, no, in a plane.

01:51:53.260 --> 01:52:12.920
And so, I was sitting there, and this tall, muscled up, must have been seven feet tall, and muscled up like Arnold Schwarzenegger, and just pale as could be, came into the room there.

01:52:12.920 --> 01:52:18.000
And I said, excuse me, can I sit by the window?

01:52:18.260 --> 01:52:22.580
He got this look of fear on his face and turned around and ran out.

01:52:22.580 --> 01:52:35.900
And so, a few minutes later, a little gray with three of these big guys huddled behind the gray for protection, you know, came in.

01:52:36.080 --> 01:52:41.280
And the gray started talking to me, and I would nod, almost going to sleep, and wake up.

01:52:42.020 --> 01:52:45.880
Finally, the gray said, you know, we've got work to do.

01:52:46.360 --> 01:52:47.080
Come with me.

01:52:47.700 --> 01:52:49.080
He took me up front.

01:52:49.200 --> 01:52:50.080
He was the pilot.

01:52:50.080 --> 01:52:56.100
And he had me kneel down in front of the control panel.

01:52:57.200 --> 01:53:02.280
With me kneeling down and him standing, we were eye to eye.

01:53:03.080 --> 01:53:05.640
So, that tells you his size, you know.

01:53:06.200 --> 01:53:08.660
But I was watching him.

01:53:09.020 --> 01:53:09.900
He was talking.

01:53:10.020 --> 01:53:11.780
We were talking to each other and all that.

01:53:12.140 --> 01:53:13.580
We would land.

01:53:14.640 --> 01:53:20.020
The tall, white guys would go out and come back in, and I guess they were picking up more people.

01:53:20.800 --> 01:53:21.880
We'd take off again.

01:53:22.000 --> 01:53:25.160
And finally, he said, we're going on a long jump now.

01:53:26.440 --> 01:53:30.420
And so, we went on this thing where we didn't land for quite a while.

01:53:30.420 --> 01:53:34.040
And I said, I've been watching.

01:53:34.200 --> 01:53:35.540
Can I try it?

01:53:36.260 --> 01:53:38.520
And he said, no, human hands are too small.

01:53:39.340 --> 01:53:41.120
Well, I have some very large hands.

01:53:42.080 --> 01:53:45.780
And so, he said, put your hand up.

01:53:46.160 --> 01:53:47.620
And I put my hand up.

01:53:47.760 --> 01:53:48.660
He put his up.

01:53:48.800 --> 01:53:50.080
And his were almost the same.

01:53:50.220 --> 01:53:52.020
We were almost the same size hands.

01:53:53.020 --> 01:53:56.980
And so, he said, I'll let you try.

01:53:58.500 --> 01:54:02.420
And I tried it and didn't wreck the place.

01:54:03.120 --> 01:54:04.360
I didn't wreck the thing.

01:54:04.440 --> 01:54:07.180
But he was standing right over me just in case, you know.

01:54:07.800 --> 01:54:09.580
And so, I tried it.

01:54:09.640 --> 01:54:10.880
And I learned how to do it.

01:54:11.020 --> 01:54:15.320
Anyway, we landed at some place that was not Earth.

01:54:15.320 --> 01:54:18.560
And the sky was black.

01:54:18.760 --> 01:54:20.660
The sun was out, but very dim.

01:54:21.920 --> 01:54:27.400
And I looked out the window, the front window.

01:54:27.940 --> 01:54:29.540
And there were two other ships.

01:54:29.540 --> 01:54:33.220
There was a string of people going.

01:54:34.160 --> 01:54:36.500
And I asked him, what do you do here?

01:54:36.580 --> 01:54:38.140
And he said, we're a medical team.

01:54:38.520 --> 01:54:44.600
He said, we catch a lot of diseases going around space.

01:54:44.700 --> 01:54:47.320
And he said, we have no immunity.

01:54:48.060 --> 01:54:51.560
But you people are like antibody factories.

01:54:51.980 --> 01:54:54.760
We use your antibodies for health.

01:54:54.760 --> 01:54:57.800
And he said, there are only three of our ships and all that.

01:54:58.700 --> 01:55:03.760
And so, anyway, came our time to get off.

01:55:04.380 --> 01:55:07.040
And I filed back with the other people.

01:55:07.520 --> 01:55:08.740
And I was getting off.

01:55:08.840 --> 01:55:15.080
And they were going up this path to a pavilion that was up on the hill.

01:55:16.080 --> 01:55:17.920
He grabbed me by the arm.

01:55:17.960 --> 01:55:19.400
And he said, you don't want to go up there.

01:55:20.680 --> 01:55:22.960
And he pulled me over to the side.

01:55:22.960 --> 01:55:25.740
And we sat down on the grass on the hillside.

01:55:25.740 --> 01:55:32.160
And the grass was totally black, which I found out from somebody later.

01:55:32.280 --> 01:55:36.840
They said, well, of course, it was black with no bright sun.

01:55:36.940 --> 01:55:38.580
It had to absorb different rays.

01:55:38.700 --> 01:55:40.440
And so, it had to be black to absorb.

01:55:40.660 --> 01:55:41.140
I don't know.

01:55:41.300 --> 01:55:43.420
They gave me a scientific reason for it.

01:55:43.420 --> 01:55:48.620
But as we sat there, we were talking.

01:55:49.400 --> 01:55:53.580
And you could hear up on the hill, somebody would scream in horror.

01:55:53.840 --> 01:55:55.880
And everybody else would laugh.

01:55:57.160 --> 01:55:58.520
And then they'd go quiet.

01:55:59.060 --> 01:56:01.340
And then somebody else would scream in horror.

01:56:01.480 --> 01:56:03.220
And everybody would laugh and all that.

01:56:03.320 --> 01:56:04.660
And they took turns.

01:56:04.660 --> 01:56:07.940
And so, I was glad I wasn't up there.

01:56:09.060 --> 01:56:12.200
But anyway, as we talked, he was answering questions.

01:56:12.220 --> 01:56:13.160
And we were talking.

01:56:13.580 --> 01:56:17.760
And I said, well, what are you implanting in us?

01:56:19.660 --> 01:56:21.200
And he was confused.

01:56:21.380 --> 01:56:24.600
He said, we don't implant anything into you.

01:56:25.180 --> 01:56:31.040
I said, well, we find these glass-like things and things like that implanted in us.

01:56:31.040 --> 01:56:34.320
And he said, oh, you people won't be still.

01:56:34.440 --> 01:56:36.020
The tips of our instruments break off.

01:56:37.640 --> 01:56:41.920
And I said, well, why do you stick those?

01:56:42.000 --> 01:56:52.780
He said, because we take one or two cells of our diseased tissue, put it on that tip and implant it into you,

01:56:52.820 --> 01:56:54.720
and you will start making antibodies.

01:56:55.800 --> 01:56:58.240
And then we come back and harvest the antibodies.

01:56:58.240 --> 01:57:00.740
And he said, you people won't be still.

01:57:00.820 --> 01:57:01.740
The tips break off.

01:57:03.140 --> 01:57:05.020
And so, that's what that was.

01:57:06.780 --> 01:57:12.180
When you say that you heard laughing and then, you know, somebody would shout out.

01:57:12.200 --> 01:57:16.920
The whole gang would laugh while somebody was screaming and just pain and horror.

01:57:17.340 --> 01:57:19.780
Do you think that was like an operation going on?

01:57:19.920 --> 01:57:21.380
They were doing something to them.

01:57:21.680 --> 01:57:22.640
I'm not sure what.

01:57:22.980 --> 01:57:24.240
This antibody infusion?

01:57:25.200 --> 01:57:26.200
I guess, yeah.

01:57:26.200 --> 01:57:28.520
Or this tissue infusion that would create the antibodies?

01:57:28.720 --> 01:57:29.380
I don't know.

01:57:29.460 --> 01:57:30.180
I wasn't up there.

01:57:30.820 --> 01:57:32.020
But that's what I'm guessing.

01:57:32.020 --> 01:57:35.340
And this is once you've landed on, do you know where this other planet is?

01:57:35.380 --> 01:57:35.960
No, I don't.

01:57:36.200 --> 01:57:36.440
Uh-oh.

01:57:36.700 --> 01:57:38.080
I just know it wasn't Earth.

01:57:38.440 --> 01:57:39.020
I knew that.

01:57:39.820 --> 01:57:44.080
Is the other guy, you know, the seven-foot guy who looked like Arnold Schwarzenegger?

01:57:44.440 --> 01:57:46.420
They were still on the ship, I guess.

01:57:46.740 --> 01:57:50.480
I was sitting there with the little gray on the hillside.

01:57:50.480 --> 01:57:54.960
So, it's like the grays and the, you know, these like Nordic-like things are working together?

01:57:56.280 --> 01:57:57.560
These weren't Nordics.

01:57:57.800 --> 01:57:58.480
What were they?

01:57:59.160 --> 01:58:03.180
They were just, they struck me as being dumb as a rock.

01:58:03.500 --> 01:58:03.700
Hmm.

01:58:03.700 --> 01:58:09.520
Oh, they were just workers for the gray.

01:58:09.940 --> 01:58:11.420
I don't know what they were doing.

01:58:11.680 --> 01:58:14.000
They were going out and getting people and coming back.

01:58:14.920 --> 01:58:16.600
How do you fly a UFO?

01:58:18.780 --> 01:58:23.680
Um, well, let me go in with the story, okay?

01:58:23.860 --> 01:58:24.260
Yeah, sure.

01:58:24.260 --> 01:58:32.260
Um, uh, when everybody came back down, uh, well, while we were there on the mountainside,

01:58:32.540 --> 01:58:39.420
on the hillside, um, the pilot said to me, I want some, I want you to meet somebody.

01:58:39.540 --> 01:58:45.660
He went off and got another one that came back, sat down on the hill behind me and said, put

01:58:45.660 --> 01:58:46.420
up your hand.

01:58:46.820 --> 01:58:48.080
So, I put up my hand.

01:58:48.160 --> 01:58:50.000
He put his hand on the back of mine.

01:58:50.000 --> 01:58:57.500
And from that point on, I remembered nothing until the people were coming back down the

01:58:57.500 --> 01:59:02.180
hill and I was in line with them getting back onto the ship.

01:59:03.140 --> 01:59:08.260
And, uh, I turned to the pilot and I said, I'd like to remember all this.

01:59:08.280 --> 01:59:09.480
And he said, well, you won't.

01:59:11.940 --> 01:59:19.820
So, the next morning, I was standing at the back window of the parsonage there, looking out

01:59:19.820 --> 01:59:23.580
I could not remember why I was there.

01:59:23.700 --> 01:59:25.640
I thought, well, I've been sleepwalking or what?

01:59:26.600 --> 01:59:31.200
And was just so confused for about five or six minutes.

01:59:31.380 --> 01:59:36.440
And then I realized, oh, yeah, I'm moving to the new parsonage.

01:59:37.500 --> 01:59:42.940
So, I gathered up the pilot that I had made, threw it into the U-Haul and drove off, thinking

01:59:42.940 --> 01:59:54.240
I've forgotten something over the next 25 years that grew and grew and grew until I couldn't

01:59:54.240 --> 01:59:56.960
leave the house without going back five times.

01:59:57.120 --> 01:59:57.920
What have I forgotten?

01:59:58.020 --> 01:59:58.740
What have I forgotten?

01:59:59.540 --> 02:00:01.460
And, uh, no matter where we lived.

02:00:01.460 --> 02:00:04.680
And so, one day, we were headed for church.

02:00:05.860 --> 02:00:11.120
And, uh, my wife was sick and tired of all this, you know.

02:00:11.700 --> 02:00:15.420
And, uh, so she said, did you check the basement?

02:00:15.700 --> 02:00:16.580
Yes, I checked the basement.

02:00:16.660 --> 02:00:17.580
Did you check the kitchen?

02:00:17.740 --> 02:00:18.680
Did you check the stove?

02:00:18.780 --> 02:00:20.440
Did you check, you know, and I said, yes.

02:00:20.700 --> 02:00:22.680
And she said, did you check the backyard?

02:00:22.680 --> 02:00:30.960
And when she said that, 25 years later, after the event, it all came flooding back.

02:00:32.580 --> 02:00:33.920
And I remembered.

02:00:35.240 --> 02:00:38.500
And I thought, this is stupid.

02:00:38.940 --> 02:00:40.340
I've never been abducted.

02:00:40.680 --> 02:00:41.680
Come on, give me a break.

02:00:42.400 --> 02:00:46.880
And, but it hit me so hard, I sat down in the front steps and I just couldn't move.

02:00:46.880 --> 02:00:54.440
And, uh, so the next day, I was in the remote viewing unit by that time.

02:00:54.780 --> 02:01:00.240
The next day, I got some encrypted coordinates, just some numbers, and I gave it to all the

02:01:00.240 --> 02:01:01.820
people as a practice target.

02:01:03.360 --> 02:01:06.540
And they came back with what I had remembered.

02:01:07.320 --> 02:01:07.640
Really?

02:01:08.360 --> 02:01:15.640
And so, I thought, telepathic overlay, they're just reading my mind.

02:01:15.640 --> 02:01:17.120
And it never happened.

02:01:18.400 --> 02:01:23.420
So, um, evidently, it was Ed Dames that reported me.

02:01:24.560 --> 02:01:30.600
And the following week, I was up at the Defense Intelligence Agency, going to see the director.

02:01:31.420 --> 02:01:37.040
And the two men in black stepped out of the north, out of a little conference room, pointed

02:01:37.040 --> 02:01:41.220
in, and I knew the routine of the men in black.

02:01:41.220 --> 02:01:45.240
And so, I went in and, uh, sat down.

02:01:46.480 --> 02:01:49.460
The men in black are not aliens, okay?

02:01:50.280 --> 02:01:54.120
They're a hired professional interrogator.

02:01:54.120 --> 02:02:03.060
And the other person who sits off to the side and never says anything is the person from

02:02:03.060 --> 02:02:07.920
a unit that has questions that they give to the interrogator.

02:02:08.060 --> 02:02:10.300
And he sits over there and listens for answers.

02:02:10.740 --> 02:02:12.740
That's why he sits over there and never says anything.

02:02:12.740 --> 02:02:18.680
And so, the interrogator has a list of questions.

02:02:18.820 --> 02:02:24.340
He jumbles them back and forth and, you know, mixes them up and says them in different ways

02:02:24.340 --> 02:02:26.100
to see if you're going to trip yourself up.

02:02:26.100 --> 02:02:31.680
And so, he was, he kept asking about the control panel.

02:02:33.320 --> 02:02:42.640
And, um, and I thought when they stepped out in the hallway, I thought they want to see

02:02:42.640 --> 02:02:44.840
if somebody with my clearance has gone crazy.

02:02:45.920 --> 02:02:50.040
So, I thought that's what it was in there for, but he kept asking about the control panel.

02:02:50.040 --> 02:02:57.660
And so, about the fourth or fifth time he asked, I said, no, this is how you work it.

02:02:58.380 --> 02:03:00.180
And explained it.

02:03:01.100 --> 02:03:06.640
And the guy over to the side slapped his leg and said, so that's it.

02:03:09.380 --> 02:03:14.520
I looked over and I realized, he's got one and didn't know how to fly it.

02:03:15.520 --> 02:03:19.820
I looked back at the interrogator and grinned.

02:03:20.840 --> 02:03:24.260
The interrogator is trained to never make an expression of any kind.

02:03:25.280 --> 02:03:27.600
But his ears started turning red.

02:03:27.660 --> 02:03:28.820
I could tell he was angry.

02:03:29.820 --> 02:03:32.860
And within 20 seconds, I was in the room by myself.

02:03:32.960 --> 02:03:33.480
They were gone.

02:03:34.740 --> 02:03:41.320
And, uh, so I thought, maybe I was abducted.

02:03:41.760 --> 02:03:42.360
I don't know.

02:03:43.020 --> 02:03:48.980
Then about a year later, I was at this facility on this other mission.

02:03:50.040 --> 02:03:55.780
I met this guy that I had known way back years before in the military.

02:03:56.600 --> 02:03:57.960
Found out what he did.

02:03:58.180 --> 02:03:59.580
He showed me through this hangar.

02:04:00.580 --> 02:04:03.900
And, um, that's where I came across this pile.

02:04:04.000 --> 02:04:05.940
And I said, that's out of a UFO.

02:04:05.940 --> 02:04:08.400
Oh, and got kicked out of there.

02:04:09.240 --> 02:04:17.200
But the minute I saw that, I thought, shit, I was abducted.

02:04:19.240 --> 02:04:21.220
What did the control panel look like?

02:04:22.480 --> 02:04:27.260
It has an impression of a hand on it.

02:04:27.500 --> 02:04:29.200
This one, the one in the hangar did.

02:04:29.800 --> 02:04:31.080
The one on the ship didn't.

02:04:31.080 --> 02:04:35.200
Um, had the impression of a hand, there are holes over it.

02:04:35.960 --> 02:04:36.280
Okay.

02:04:37.400 --> 02:04:48.040
And, uh, where you put your finger over the hole is what works the, uh, works the, controls the ship.

02:04:48.040 --> 02:04:51.500
Any sort of surface materials, metallic?

02:04:52.880 --> 02:04:53.360
Metal.

02:04:53.700 --> 02:04:53.960
Metal.

02:04:54.520 --> 02:04:55.400
But, um.

02:04:55.500 --> 02:04:56.000
Is it gray?

02:04:56.300 --> 02:04:57.080
It's the holes.

02:04:57.660 --> 02:04:58.220
The holes.

02:04:58.860 --> 02:05:03.040
Where you put your, where you stop one of the holes up, that's how they control the ship.

02:05:03.500 --> 02:05:06.380
Was it gray or any particular color?

02:05:08.140 --> 02:05:10.860
It was just metal, as far as I remember.

02:05:11.320 --> 02:05:11.440
Yeah.

02:05:11.440 --> 02:05:17.840
And so, when you said, I think that's a control panel from a UFO, you clearly hit a nerve.

02:05:18.580 --> 02:05:20.520
I said, that's out of a UFO.

02:05:21.700 --> 02:05:24.420
I was, definite statement, that's out of a UFO.

02:05:24.680 --> 02:05:26.460
And it just echoed in that hangar.

02:05:27.180 --> 02:05:27.460
And, uh.

02:05:27.700 --> 02:05:29.300
And they got angry immediately.

02:05:29.600 --> 02:05:30.040
Oh, yeah.

02:05:30.500 --> 02:05:31.920
They kicked me out, man.

02:05:32.680 --> 02:05:34.120
Uh, with warnings.

02:05:34.480 --> 02:05:35.380
They kicked me out.

02:05:36.020 --> 02:05:36.300
Yeah.

02:05:36.960 --> 02:05:38.120
What, what were the warnings?

02:05:38.460 --> 02:05:40.180
You don't tell this about anybody.

02:05:40.180 --> 02:05:45.320
We, you know, uh, you don't ever mention this about anybody.

02:05:46.400 --> 02:05:48.320
Why do you feel okay talking about it now?

02:05:49.000 --> 02:05:50.980
Uh, because I can talk about it.

02:05:51.160 --> 02:05:52.980
I can't tell you where it is.

02:05:53.280 --> 02:05:54.940
No context is okay.

02:05:55.120 --> 02:05:55.400
Yeah.

02:05:55.660 --> 02:05:55.920
Uh-huh.

02:05:56.080 --> 02:05:56.400
Yeah.

02:05:57.100 --> 02:05:59.360
And, uh, when were you abducted?

02:05:59.420 --> 02:05:59.840
What year?

02:06:02.220 --> 02:06:04.940
Uh, it was 25 years before that.

02:06:04.940 --> 02:06:14.380
So, it would be, uh, 60, 63, 65, somewhere around there.

02:06:14.480 --> 02:06:14.720
Sure.

02:06:14.900 --> 02:06:18.540
And was it, uh, from your place in, were you in New Mexico at the time?

02:06:18.720 --> 02:06:18.740
Or?

02:06:18.800 --> 02:06:19.820
No, it was in Texas.

02:06:19.960 --> 02:06:20.480
You're in Texas.

02:06:20.560 --> 02:06:20.880
Um.

02:06:21.680 --> 02:06:22.120
Um.

02:06:22.120 --> 02:06:25.080
Um, in East Texas, East Texas Church, yeah.

02:06:25.480 --> 02:06:25.720
Hmm.

02:06:26.020 --> 02:06:28.880
And did that have any transform?

02:06:28.980 --> 02:06:33.500
You mentioned some abductees, you know, have greater psychic powers.

02:06:33.620 --> 02:06:36.160
Did that, you know, change you in any sort of way?

02:06:36.900 --> 02:06:38.100
I don't think so.

02:06:39.100 --> 02:06:49.420
Um, like I say, growing up, when I was 12 and 15, I was all this PK stuff.

02:06:49.420 --> 02:06:58.720
And, uh, I had had some psychic experiences when I was young and all through life, but nothing

02:06:58.720 --> 02:07:01.100
astounding of any way.

02:07:01.940 --> 02:07:11.000
And then when Bert put me into the remote viewing unit, that's where I learned the controlled

02:07:11.000 --> 02:07:15.920
remote viewing to use your psychic ability to collect intelligence.

02:07:16.420 --> 02:07:16.500
Hmm.

02:07:17.500 --> 02:07:18.860
So fascinating.

02:07:18.860 --> 02:07:19.580
Hmm.

02:07:21.380 --> 02:07:25.660
How long do you, do you feel like you were on this UFO for when you were abducted?

02:07:26.160 --> 02:07:33.160
Well, it was, it felt like hours and, oh, it felt like a long time.

02:07:33.480 --> 02:07:36.820
Did you have missing time at all, like in, in the real world?

02:07:37.600 --> 02:07:42.500
Well, I was there on the pallet in the living room.

02:07:42.500 --> 02:07:49.000
Um, and the next morning I was standing at the back window looking out at the backyard.

02:07:50.360 --> 02:07:54.260
So it had to be just overnight, you know?

02:07:54.260 --> 02:07:59.360
Did anyone in your family ask what had happened to you?

02:08:00.060 --> 02:08:07.260
No, because when I left and went to the new parsonage, I felt like I'd forgotten something

02:08:07.260 --> 02:08:12.720
at the other parsonage, but I didn't remember any of it for 25 years.

02:08:12.720 --> 02:08:20.340
Until, so was it, it was the control panel that you saw in the hangar that freaked you out and

02:08:20.340 --> 02:08:21.620
made you remember the abduction?

02:08:21.620 --> 02:08:21.880
No.

02:08:22.280 --> 02:08:25.760
It was when my wife said, did you check the backyard?

02:08:26.060 --> 02:08:26.480
Okay.

02:08:26.480 --> 02:08:32.480
And she was making fun of me, but when she said that, it all came back.

02:08:33.220 --> 02:08:33.740
Really?

02:08:34.120 --> 02:08:41.220
And so the next Monday, I went to work there at the remote viewing unit, gave them the task

02:08:41.220 --> 02:08:42.260
and they confirmed it.

02:08:42.360 --> 02:08:43.200
I didn't believe it.

02:08:44.420 --> 02:08:46.180
The men in black confirmed it.

02:08:46.260 --> 02:08:47.080
I didn't believe it.

02:08:47.080 --> 02:08:55.820
And a year later, I saw that pile of stuff in that hangar, saw the control panel, and

02:08:55.820 --> 02:09:00.460
that's when I said, shit, I was abducted.

02:09:02.220 --> 02:09:02.860
Got it.

02:09:02.960 --> 02:09:08.200
So you had the flashback when your wife said, go check the backyard.

02:09:08.540 --> 02:09:10.820
Yeah, but that was...

02:09:10.820 --> 02:09:12.520
Why did that give you the flashback?

02:09:12.520 --> 02:09:20.480
Well, evidently, because when that happened, I was trying to get up and go to the backyard

02:09:20.480 --> 02:09:22.960
and see what happened, what landed.

02:09:25.040 --> 02:09:27.500
And so I didn't remember the whole...

02:09:27.500 --> 02:09:29.200
I didn't remember any of it.

02:09:29.720 --> 02:09:39.380
When I drove away from the parsonage that day to go to the new house, all I could think

02:09:39.380 --> 02:09:46.000
of was how to get to the new house, and also the feeling that, hey, I forgot something.

02:09:46.800 --> 02:09:51.040
Did you have an implant at any point in your body afterwards that you found?

02:09:52.380 --> 02:09:55.960
He grabbed me by the arm and he said, you don't want to go up there.

02:09:57.260 --> 02:09:59.700
So how do you fly a UFO?

02:10:00.160 --> 02:10:03.300
Because presumably this gray sort of taught you.

02:10:03.420 --> 02:10:08.780
He showed me the fingering and all that, and that's when I explained to the interrogator

02:10:08.780 --> 02:10:13.680
and that's when the guy said, slapped his leg, said, so that's it.

02:10:14.060 --> 02:10:16.200
Is there some sort of mental connection?

02:10:16.540 --> 02:10:16.800
No.

02:10:17.380 --> 02:10:18.920
Just putting the fingers...

02:10:18.920 --> 02:10:20.600
Just how you work the control panel.

02:10:20.780 --> 02:10:25.680
Because if I was the guy in the hangar, you said they had other crashed, you know, prosaic...

02:10:25.680 --> 02:10:26.880
Well, they had crashed airplanes.

02:10:27.020 --> 02:10:27.580
Crashed airplanes.

02:10:27.720 --> 02:10:27.900
Yeah.

02:10:27.900 --> 02:10:33.120
So if I had other crashed airplanes and I was an aerospace person and I saw a control panel

02:10:33.120 --> 02:10:38.960
and it had, like, you know, five different little holes for your fingers...

02:10:38.960 --> 02:10:40.040
It had a bunch of holes, yeah.

02:10:40.200 --> 02:10:46.480
So my maybe, like, initial assumption would be that's how you, you know, fly it.

02:10:46.500 --> 02:10:48.260
But he didn't figure that out on his own.

02:10:48.460 --> 02:10:53.740
I imagine a regular or an optics person would think, what a piece of junk.

02:10:53.780 --> 02:10:54.360
Yeah, or that.

02:10:54.500 --> 02:10:55.520
Or they just would have no idea.

02:10:55.520 --> 02:10:57.680
So he didn't even know it was a control panel.

02:10:58.020 --> 02:10:58.240
Yeah.

02:10:58.480 --> 02:10:58.700
Yeah.

02:10:59.060 --> 02:10:59.460
Interesting.

02:10:59.500 --> 02:11:02.500
But evidently, somebody knew it was a control panel.

02:11:02.540 --> 02:11:04.460
Because they got mad and kicked you out.

02:11:04.660 --> 02:11:04.980
Yeah.

02:11:06.540 --> 02:11:09.400
But it was just sitting there, like, kind of unattended to?

02:11:09.760 --> 02:11:11.660
It was in a pile over to one side.

02:11:12.180 --> 02:11:12.620
Interesting.

02:11:13.100 --> 02:11:13.320
Yeah.

02:11:13.860 --> 02:11:14.900
So bizarre.

02:11:15.240 --> 02:11:17.520
Was this...

02:11:17.520 --> 02:11:20.760
Do you think they had any intention of reverse engineering it?

02:11:21.300 --> 02:11:22.260
I have no idea.

02:11:22.260 --> 02:11:27.740
We just were walking past pile of wreckage, pile of wreckage, pile of wreckage, and there

02:11:27.740 --> 02:11:33.100
was this one pile of wreckage, and there was that control panel sitting up there.

02:11:33.360 --> 02:11:37.720
Did you experience any sort of psychic phenomena, like, around the metal?

02:11:37.840 --> 02:11:39.760
That sometimes occurs.

02:11:40.760 --> 02:11:41.100
No.

02:11:41.560 --> 02:11:42.360
It was just there.

02:11:42.420 --> 02:11:45.920
I just saw it, and, hey, that's out of UFO.

02:11:46.420 --> 02:11:46.860
Wow.

02:11:46.860 --> 02:11:47.300
So...

02:11:47.300 --> 02:11:49.380
It's pretty wild.

02:11:49.700 --> 02:11:49.960
Yeah.

02:11:50.640 --> 02:11:57.060
Has anyone else showed you a photo or a drawing of their abduction experience that looks at

02:11:57.060 --> 02:11:59.140
all like this control panel that you saw?

02:11:59.260 --> 02:11:59.520
No.

02:11:59.940 --> 02:12:00.640
Not a one.

02:12:01.360 --> 02:12:04.400
But then they never show you the inside of the ship, I don't think.

02:12:06.000 --> 02:12:07.700
I've never seen anything like that.

02:12:07.700 --> 02:12:12.700
I mean, they tell stories about their abduction and all that, but...

02:12:12.700 --> 02:12:18.400
Did you ever come across a guy named General William Neal McCasland?

02:12:18.980 --> 02:12:19.420
No.

02:12:19.740 --> 02:12:20.800
Who's at Wright-Patterson?

02:12:21.060 --> 02:12:21.920
No, I didn't know that.

02:12:22.740 --> 02:12:26.080
Did you ever come across Hans Adams, by any chance?

02:12:26.260 --> 02:12:26.480
No.

02:12:26.480 --> 02:12:28.520
The Lichtenstein royal prince?

02:12:28.860 --> 02:12:28.920
No.

02:12:28.920 --> 02:12:29.120
No.

02:12:29.340 --> 02:12:29.660
Okay.

02:12:29.660 --> 02:12:37.940
In fact, the UFOs that...

02:12:37.940 --> 02:12:41.400
I've seen a lot of UFOs.

02:12:41.460 --> 02:12:42.840
I mean, I live in Alamogordo.

02:12:42.940 --> 02:12:44.360
We see UFOs all the time.

02:12:45.100 --> 02:12:47.400
And, I mean, provable UFOs.

02:12:50.200 --> 02:12:54.400
And it's gotten to where...

02:12:54.400 --> 02:12:55.920
Yeah, it's a UFO.

02:12:56.420 --> 02:12:56.820
So?

02:12:57.920 --> 02:12:58.480
Yeah.

02:12:58.480 --> 02:12:59.320
So what?

02:13:00.460 --> 02:13:01.720
And they're here.

02:13:01.940 --> 02:13:02.640
I know it.

02:13:03.800 --> 02:13:04.360
So?

02:13:05.520 --> 02:13:06.360
So what?

02:13:06.540 --> 02:13:07.920
There's nothing I can do about it.

02:13:08.160 --> 02:13:12.980
Do you think there's also a lineage of exotic propulsion that's man-made?

02:13:14.200 --> 02:13:25.660
What my friend who did the technology transfer with one of the groups of aliens told me at one time,

02:13:25.660 --> 02:13:26.920
he said,

02:13:27.600 --> 02:13:33.320
way back when we found that if you explode something, it moves things.

02:13:33.920 --> 02:13:35.280
It blows things away.

02:13:35.740 --> 02:13:38.600
So you can cause motion by exploding things.

02:13:38.600 --> 02:13:46.260
And that has led to the internal combustion engine and the jet plane and all that to explode and makes things move.

02:13:46.260 --> 02:13:55.480
He said that the group he dealt with way back when they found that you can move things with magnets.

02:13:55.480 --> 02:14:08.560
And that just as we have taken the fire and turned it into rockets that can go to other planets, you know, that can go to the moon.

02:14:08.560 --> 02:14:14.260
And then they have taken magnetism and over the centuries, they have developed it to where?

02:14:15.080 --> 02:14:23.540
And he said one of the things that he had seen was that we think they're so more advanced than we are.

02:14:23.540 --> 02:14:33.040
They think we're so far advanced than they are, when actually we've just advanced in two different directions.

02:14:34.700 --> 02:14:37.380
But he said, that's why they're eager to trade with us.

02:14:39.240 --> 02:14:39.760
Interesting.

02:14:40.100 --> 02:14:44.760
Because we've like almost split off from them as far as our trajectories.

02:14:45.000 --> 02:14:45.200
Yeah.

02:14:45.520 --> 02:14:48.320
Is there anything having to do with timelines?

02:14:48.320 --> 02:14:52.120
Like, are they us on a different timeline sort of thing?

02:14:53.040 --> 02:14:56.820
Not from anything I've heard him say.

02:14:57.680 --> 02:15:02.200
Did you ever encounter any religious figures in your experience with remote viewing?

02:15:02.980 --> 02:15:03.520
Oh, yeah.

02:15:04.240 --> 02:15:04.700
Like who?

02:15:04.980 --> 02:15:10.320
Yeah, but not tied with ETs or anything like that.

02:15:10.340 --> 02:15:14.500
Were you ever tasked with looking into the Buddha or Jesus or Muhammad?

02:15:14.500 --> 02:15:15.120
Oh, yeah. Absolutely, yeah.

02:15:15.440 --> 02:15:16.740
Which one of those?

02:15:16.740 --> 02:15:23.420
Two that were most meaningful to me.

02:15:24.360 --> 02:15:33.080
One time, well, I think we already mentioned that one of my fortes was mental excess.

02:15:34.440 --> 02:15:44.540
And so I was tasked a lot of times with doing personality profiles or, even deeper than that,

02:15:44.540 --> 02:15:47.740
getting the plans and intentions of foreign leaders.

02:15:48.860 --> 02:15:53.660
And personality profile is just where you give a personality profile of.

02:15:53.660 --> 02:15:59.560
So I went over one day, and they said, we have a personality profile for you.

02:16:00.680 --> 02:16:02.320
And they gave me the coordinates.

02:16:03.220 --> 02:16:11.940
And just almost immediately, I said, this isn't one of the bad guys.

02:16:11.940 --> 02:16:18.920
And my monitor said, well, your task with it, go ahead and do the session.

02:16:20.000 --> 02:16:27.560
By the end of that session, I was just feeling like I was glowing.

02:16:27.560 --> 02:16:36.640
And my entire summary on that session was, whatever evil you think this guy did, he didn't do it.

02:16:37.300 --> 02:16:38.180
He's a good guy.

02:16:38.180 --> 02:16:46.860
And in that session, I found myself, again, with the perfect side integration.

02:16:46.860 --> 02:16:58.300
I was standing there, and this little Jewish-looking guy was standing in front of me in a modern business suit.

02:16:59.880 --> 02:17:09.280
And we didn't talk so much as just, you know, related to each other and all that.

02:17:09.280 --> 02:17:15.820
And I felt just dirty in front of this guy.

02:17:16.960 --> 02:17:25.540
And basically, what he let me know was, whatever evil you've done, I've seen a whole lot worse.

02:17:26.760 --> 02:17:30.660
Whatever good you've done, I've seen a whole lot better.

02:17:31.780 --> 02:17:32.940
And I don't care.

02:17:33.040 --> 02:17:33.780
I like you anyway.

02:17:33.780 --> 02:17:40.120
And when I came out of the session, that's what I knew.

02:17:40.240 --> 02:17:44.660
But what I wrote was, whatever evil you think this guy did, he didn't do it.

02:17:45.080 --> 02:17:46.180
You know, this is a good guy.

02:17:47.080 --> 02:17:52.280
And that's when the monitor opened the envelope.

02:17:53.100 --> 02:17:56.700
And our director had written the word Jesus on it.

02:17:56.700 --> 02:18:07.120
And so, I cannot say I've physically met Jesus, but I have had the experience of it.

02:18:07.580 --> 02:18:09.380
And it changed my life.

02:18:09.580 --> 02:18:10.240
It really did.

02:18:10.700 --> 02:18:12.720
What did you feel when you were in his presence?

02:18:13.040 --> 02:18:14.360
Oh, I felt dirty.

02:18:15.200 --> 02:18:16.760
I felt so dirty.

02:18:17.060 --> 02:18:20.120
I felt so guilty of myself and everything else.

02:18:20.260 --> 02:18:21.280
I felt, you know.

02:18:21.700 --> 02:18:22.660
But you felt loved?

02:18:22.940 --> 02:18:23.240
Huh?

02:18:23.540 --> 02:18:24.760
Did you also feel loved?

02:18:24.760 --> 02:18:25.820
Oh, yeah, absolutely.

02:18:26.700 --> 02:18:28.140
When he said, I don't care.

02:18:28.800 --> 02:18:30.800
He said, I love you anyway, you know.

02:18:31.620 --> 02:18:36.380
And why was he, you don't think of Jesus in a, you know, business seat?

02:18:36.500 --> 02:18:37.380
Why do you think he was?

02:18:37.780 --> 02:18:48.600
I think that was a way of saying he's not a thing out of the past and, you know, wearing robes and all that.

02:18:48.700 --> 02:18:49.520
He's here today.

02:18:51.160 --> 02:18:54.980
That's the only interpretation I can get of that.

02:18:54.980 --> 02:18:58.520
Did he look like Jesus is traditionally depicted, long hair?

02:18:58.520 --> 02:18:59.060
No, nowhere near.

02:18:59.320 --> 02:19:00.080
No, no.

02:19:01.140 --> 02:19:03.460
I mean, this looked like a short little Jewish guy.

02:19:04.360 --> 02:19:05.200
Where was he?

02:19:05.400 --> 02:19:06.700
And what was he just kind of?

02:19:07.160 --> 02:19:08.860
He was just standing there in front of me.

02:19:09.020 --> 02:19:09.320
Yeah.

02:19:09.660 --> 02:19:11.940
In like hyperspace or in a room or?

02:19:12.040 --> 02:19:12.480
In a room.

02:19:12.680 --> 02:19:12.900
Okay.

02:19:12.900 --> 02:19:15.800
And it was all dark in the room, but we were there, you know.

02:19:15.940 --> 02:19:16.260
Wow.

02:19:16.580 --> 02:19:17.240
And, uh.

02:19:17.860 --> 02:19:22.540
Did you ever remote view any other religious figures or mystics?

02:19:22.860 --> 02:19:23.920
One other time.

02:19:23.920 --> 02:19:28.660
Uh, they had done this with, um, uh, Bill Ray.

02:19:29.680 --> 02:19:32.040
And, uh, they did it with me.

02:19:32.640 --> 02:19:34.500
Uh, they probably did it with all the others.

02:19:35.260 --> 02:19:42.460
Um, uh, I was to do a, you know, just a target.

02:19:42.580 --> 02:19:45.400
They didn't even say personality profile or anything like that.

02:19:45.400 --> 02:19:52.580
And, uh, I found myself surrounded by total darkness, but I was standing in some light.

02:19:52.980 --> 02:19:55.020
I couldn't figure out where the light was coming from.

02:19:56.160 --> 02:20:08.240
And, uh, I heard this voice that said, you know, um, um, you know, welcome to me and all that.

02:20:10.080 --> 02:20:14.600
And I said, well, what am I doing here?

02:20:15.400 --> 02:20:17.800
And I said, you're here to learn.

02:20:18.560 --> 02:20:21.900
And I said, okay, what am I supposed to learn?

02:20:23.140 --> 02:20:25.200
And there was no answer.

02:20:26.220 --> 02:20:31.060
And I said, well, look, give me something.

02:20:32.720 --> 02:20:37.340
And the voice said, I've given you everything you need.

02:20:38.380 --> 02:20:42.860
What I give you now, I give through you, not to you.

02:20:42.860 --> 02:20:49.680
And when I came out of the session and they opened the envelope, it said God.

02:20:50.780 --> 02:20:51.260
Really?

02:20:51.560 --> 02:20:51.840
Yeah.

02:20:52.260 --> 02:20:54.720
Did you see God?

02:20:54.860 --> 02:20:55.420
I didn't.

02:20:55.840 --> 02:20:57.380
But I heard the voice clearly.

02:20:57.960 --> 02:21:03.680
From now on, everything I give you, I give through you, not to you.

02:21:03.800 --> 02:21:05.560
What did you feel in God's presence?

02:21:05.560 --> 02:21:09.140
Oh, total confusion.

02:21:10.800 --> 02:21:13.460
I was, I was thinking, hey, I've got a target.

02:21:13.680 --> 02:21:18.640
I've got, I've got to write a report on this, you know, but, uh.

02:21:18.740 --> 02:21:20.140
Did you feel awestruck?

02:21:21.220 --> 02:21:21.680
No.

02:21:21.900 --> 02:21:25.920
I was in an empty room hearing a voice.

02:21:26.300 --> 02:21:27.800
Did you feel love?

02:21:27.800 --> 02:21:30.380
Not really.

02:21:31.200 --> 02:21:44.160
Oh, the voice was, I mean, just more friendly than you'd ever know, you know, and kind and all that.

02:21:44.400 --> 02:21:46.060
Do you think you actually spoke to God?

02:21:46.060 --> 02:21:53.480
Um, I think God spoke to me, yeah.

02:21:54.740 --> 02:22:02.240
And I think what I was there to learn was, from now on, I give through you, not to you.

02:22:03.380 --> 02:22:11.320
Do you think on the remote viewing program, anybody ever engaged in sort of deception or trickery?

02:22:11.480 --> 02:22:13.440
Or do you think it was always pretty straightforward?

02:22:14.180 --> 02:22:15.060
They gave you a target?

02:22:15.060 --> 02:22:19.620
Well, we had constructive trickery.

02:22:20.540 --> 02:22:33.160
Um, I know one time, um, we had one of the viewers go over, and one of the things you have to learn in remote viewing is how to overcome pollution.

02:22:34.340 --> 02:22:37.160
And so, we were never supposed to pollute each other.

02:22:38.800 --> 02:22:42.840
But you don't learn how to overcome pollution by not facing it.

02:22:42.840 --> 02:22:51.000
And so, uh, one time, one of the viewers was going over, and he'd been having trouble with fighting pollution.

02:22:51.000 --> 02:22:59.920
And so, we had the coffee pot, and he always got coffee to take over with him to the other building when he did a session.

02:22:59.920 --> 02:23:02.780
And it was a practice session.

02:23:03.660 --> 02:23:07.660
And so, I went out and got my coffee at the same time.

02:23:07.660 --> 02:23:18.820
And right as he finished fixing his coffee and turned to go away, I said, oh, by the way, your target today is probably not the Eiffel Tower.

02:23:18.820 --> 02:23:28.920
And I turned and I turned and left him standing there having to fight the Eiffel Tower.

02:23:30.600 --> 02:23:33.300
And we would do things like that to each other, you know.

02:23:33.780 --> 02:23:37.420
Why do you think they asked you to remote view God and Jesus?

02:23:37.420 --> 02:23:41.780
It was, I think, something they did for all of us.

02:23:43.120 --> 02:23:43.440
Why?

02:23:44.020 --> 02:23:48.960
They, Bill Ray, I know, they had him remote view Buddha.

02:23:49.340 --> 02:23:54.560
And that was a life-changing experience for him.

02:23:54.560 --> 02:24:02.520
And, uh, I think they did that to all of us, just, um, just to give us the experience.

02:24:03.040 --> 02:24:09.920
Um, many of the targets we got were to gain experience in how to view things.

02:24:10.820 --> 02:24:14.040
Did you view anything historical that they wanted?

02:24:14.120 --> 02:24:16.960
Like, did they ever say, look at the French Revolution?

02:24:17.120 --> 02:24:17.420
Oh, yeah.

02:24:17.500 --> 02:24:18.900
Or look at the, you know, um.

02:24:18.960 --> 02:24:21.100
We did those because there was feedback.

02:24:21.100 --> 02:24:26.540
They wouldn't give us targets for which there was no feedback because you can't judge.

02:24:26.740 --> 02:24:30.120
What's an example of a famous historical event that you remote viewed?

02:24:30.180 --> 02:24:33.920
Oh, things like, um, Joan of Arc.

02:24:34.600 --> 02:24:35.000
Oh.

02:24:35.260 --> 02:24:36.540
What did, what did Joan of Arc?

02:24:37.140 --> 02:24:39.460
What did, what did those two look like?

02:24:39.840 --> 02:24:45.640
Um, Joan of Arc, uh, different parts of her life.

02:24:45.640 --> 02:24:54.060
Um, we also, um, um, um, just events in history, uh, historical places.

02:24:54.380 --> 02:24:55.780
What was Napoleon like?

02:24:56.580 --> 02:25:03.160
Um, Napoleon was, um, just egotistical like you wouldn't believe.

02:25:04.720 --> 02:25:10.660
I mean, he was God's favorite in all this, you know.

02:25:10.660 --> 02:25:16.520
And, uh, and he was, he was his own hero.

02:25:17.360 --> 02:25:22.580
Is there anything you can say about Napoleon that isn't conventionally known, but that you

02:25:22.580 --> 02:25:24.980
learned through your remote viewing of him?

02:25:24.980 --> 02:25:26.680
I'm not sure it was conventionally known.

02:25:27.280 --> 02:25:32.060
Well, I think people think of him as like this, yeah, chip on his shoulder because his

02:25:32.060 --> 02:25:32.680
dad was.

02:25:32.720 --> 02:25:33.160
Oh, did he?

02:25:33.480 --> 02:25:34.000
Yeah, yeah.

02:25:34.000 --> 02:25:36.000
Because his dad was a Corsican governor.

02:25:36.000 --> 02:25:40.060
So that was off the coast of France and, you know, he didn't.

02:25:40.440 --> 02:25:45.560
Well, the one thing that I really know about him is the time that, uh, he had the war of

02:25:45.560 --> 02:25:46.140
the rabbits.

02:25:46.660 --> 02:25:47.680
Have you heard of that one?

02:25:47.780 --> 02:25:48.120
No.

02:25:48.660 --> 02:25:53.860
Um, it was a celebration of some big event that he did.

02:25:54.400 --> 02:26:01.900
And, um, so he was going to have all of his generals come out to do a rabbit hunt,

02:26:02.000 --> 02:26:02.980
a wild rabbit hunt.

02:26:02.980 --> 02:26:06.500
And they couldn't find enough rabbits.

02:26:06.640 --> 02:26:11.320
So they got all these tame rabbits from rabbit raisers and all that.

02:26:12.060 --> 02:26:16.680
And right before the thing event, they let them loose in the woods.

02:26:17.740 --> 02:26:23.720
Well, the rabbits saw the humans and thought, oh, feeding time.

02:26:23.720 --> 02:26:30.660
And so all the rabbits ran toward the generals and just swarmed the generals.

02:26:31.080 --> 02:26:36.840
And the generals started running and Napoleon himself had to jump into his cart.

02:26:36.900 --> 02:26:42.340
There were hundreds of them had to jump into his cart, uh, you know, into his carriage.

02:26:42.700 --> 02:26:46.280
And as the carriage went away, he was throwing rabbits out the window.

02:26:46.520 --> 02:26:48.340
He lost the war to the rabbits.

02:26:48.880 --> 02:26:49.220
Whoa.

02:26:49.500 --> 02:26:50.740
Is this documented?

02:26:51.040 --> 02:26:51.940
Yeah, it's documented.

02:26:51.940 --> 02:26:52.960
And you saw it.

02:26:53.500 --> 02:26:53.960
Oh, yeah.

02:26:54.260 --> 02:26:54.500
Uh-huh.

02:26:54.680 --> 02:26:59.200
And, uh, I give it now as a, um, as a target to my students.

02:26:59.360 --> 02:26:59.460
Yeah.

02:26:59.680 --> 02:27:02.860
What's the most disturbing thing you've ever seen historically?

02:27:04.340 --> 02:27:06.500
Oh, historically?

02:27:06.700 --> 02:27:07.640
Or not historically.

02:27:07.880 --> 02:27:08.060
Yeah.

02:27:08.060 --> 02:27:09.740
Could have been contemporary or historically.

02:27:09.740 --> 02:27:18.900
Um, there are a lot of, um, inhumanities that humans do.

02:27:19.600 --> 02:27:30.560
And, um, I know a lot of police work, um, finding missing children.

02:27:30.560 --> 02:27:35.600
I have a lot of students who come and they say, well, I want to help find missing children.

02:27:36.500 --> 02:27:38.220
And I warn them ahead of time.

02:27:39.100 --> 02:27:45.680
In order to do that, you're going to have to experience where the children are, what they're

02:27:45.680 --> 02:27:46.940
going through and all that.

02:27:46.940 --> 02:27:58.440
And you're going to actually experience children being molested, killed, chopped into pieces and

02:27:58.440 --> 02:28:00.520
buried across acres of land.

02:28:00.900 --> 02:28:03.160
Do you really want to do that?

02:28:03.740 --> 02:28:04.040
You know?

02:28:04.040 --> 02:28:11.080
And I always tell beginning students, do not get involved in this until you're highly,

02:28:11.260 --> 02:28:11.980
highly trained.

02:28:12.340 --> 02:28:16.540
Because it can mess you up emotionally like you wouldn't believe.

02:28:16.680 --> 02:28:20.800
I mean, highly trained and highly, highly desensitized.

02:28:20.920 --> 02:28:26.260
I don't know how anybody wouldn't be, you know, broken into many pieces emotionally.

02:28:26.440 --> 02:28:26.760
Oh, yeah.

02:28:26.860 --> 02:28:28.820
Oh, it can, it can be.

02:28:29.620 --> 02:28:30.060
Jesus.

02:28:30.240 --> 02:28:30.700
Really bad.

